2 older checkpoints skipped)\\n```\\n\\nNow here are the two UX options for rewind:\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Option A: Match `entire resume` behavior — auto-resolve to latest\\n\\nThe squash merge commit appears as **one entry** in the rewind list (like today), but it restores the **latest** checkpoint instead of the first one found. The user sees:\\n\\n```\\n? Select a rewind point:\\n  > [1h ago] Committed: abc1234 — \\\"Add auth system (#42)\\\"  (logs only, 3 checkpoints)\\n```\\n\\nAfter selecting it, the existing logs-only sub-menu appears. The CLI restores the latest checkpoint's transcript and prints:\\n\\n```\\nFound 3 checkpoints in squash commit abc1234, restoring from the latest (2 older skipped)\\nRestored session: 2026-03-04-session-3\\nResume with: claude -r 2026-03-04-session-3\\n```\\n\\n**Pros:**\\n- Consistent with `entire resume` behavior\\n- Simple — no extra interaction step\\n- Usually what you want (the latest checkpoint has the most context)\\n\\n**Cons:**\\n- Older checkpoints from the squash are still inaccessible — if you specifically wanted checkpoint 1 of 3, you can't get it\\n- The \\\"(3 checkpoints)\\\" label hints at data the user can't actually reach\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Option B: Expand into separate rewind points per checkpoint\\n\\nEach checkpoint in the squash merge gets its own entry in the rewind list:\\n\\n```\\n? Select a rewind point:\\n  > [1h ago] Committed: abc1234 — \\\"Add auth tests\\\" (3/3)           (logs only)\\n    [1h ago] Committed: abc1234 — \\\"Add auth endpoints\\\" (2/3)       (logs only)\\n    [1h ago] Committed: abc1234 — \\\"Add auth model\\\" (1/3)           (logs only)\\n```\\n\\nEach entry has its own `CheckpointID` and maps to a distinct set of session transcripts on `entire/checkpoints/v1`. Selecting any one of them goes through the normal logs-only sub-menu and restores that specific checkpoint's data.\\n\\n**Pros:**\\n- Full access to all checkpoint data — nothing is silently lost\\n- User can pick exactly which point in the squash they want\\n- Each checkpoint may have different sessions/transcripts, and the user can see that\\n\\n**Cons:**\\n- Squash merges with many commits could bloat the list (10 commits = 10 entries from one squash)\\n- Slightly inconsistent with `entire resume` (which auto-picks latest)\\n- The entries share the same commit hash, which could look odd\\n\\n---\\n\\n### My take\\n\\n**Option A is the right call.** Here's why:\\n\\n1. **Consistency matters.** `entire resume` already established the pattern: squash merge → resolve to latest. Users who learn one command won't be surprised by the other.\\n\\n2. **Rewind's purpose for logs-only points is transcript restoration.** You're not restoring files (the squash commit is already on the branch). The latest checkpoint's transcript is almost always the one you want — it has the full conversation context up to that point.\\n\\n3. **Option B's benefit is theoretical.** In practice, if someone squash-merged 3 commits, they almost certainly want to resume from where they left off (the latest), not from checkpoint 1 of 3 where the agent had barely started. The rare case where you'd want an older checkpoint from a squash doesn't justify complicating the list for everyone.\\n\\n4. **The fix is minimal.** Swap `ParseCheckpoint` for `ParseAllCheckpoints` + `resolveLatestCheckpoint()` (or a shared helper), and you're done. The existing `RestoreLogsOnly()` already handles multi-session checkpoints correctly downstream.\\n\\nWhat's your preference?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":2917,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":49620,\"output_tokens\":969,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":2917,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYixVxQBC